## Task 7 — Troubleshooting Log

### Issue 1: SSH Connection Timed Out

|Field       |Detail                                                                                      |
|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Problem** |`ssh` command hung indefinitely with no response                                            |
|**Cause**   |Route table was not associated with the public subnet                                       |
|**Solution**|Went to VPC → Route Tables → Subnet Associations and linked `public-subnet-1` to `public-rt`|

-----

### Issue 2: Permission Denied (publickey)

|Field       |Detail                                                        |
|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Problem** |`Permission denied (publickey)` error when running `ssh`      |
|**Cause**   |The `.pem` file had permissions `644`, which OpenSSH rejects  |
|**Solution**|Ran `chmod 400 project-key.pem` to restrict to owner-read-only|

-----

### Issue 3: Web Page Not Loading in Browser

|Field       |Detail                                                          |
|------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Problem** |Browser showed “This site can’t be reached” after Nginx install |
|**Cause**   |Security Group was missing the inbound rule for port 80         |
|**Solution**|Added inbound rule: Type = HTTP, Port = 80, Source = `0.0.0.0/0`|

-----

## Bonus — Personal Portfolio Page

The default Nginx page was replaced with a custom personal DevOps portfolio page, deployed directly on the EC2 instance.

### Steps Taken

```bash
# SSH into instance
ssh -i project-key.pem ubuntu@<44.200.163.228>

# Open the Nginx web root index file
sudo nano /var/www/html/index.html

# Set correct ownership and permissions
sudo chown www-data:www-data /var/www/html/index.html
sudo chmod 644 /var/www/html/index.html

# Reload Nginx to serve the new page
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

### Portfolio Page in Browser

![Portfolio Page](screenshots/portfolio-browser.png)

> Custom personal portfolio page live at `http://[YOUR PUBLIC IP HERE]`, replacing the default Nginx welcome page.

